      <section id="panel-dictionary" class="section">
        <div class="section__header"><span class="section__badge">Data Tables</span><h2 class="section__title">Gen3 - CDE Data Tables</h2></div>
        <p>Comprehensive documentation of the data structure and fields within the CDNM Gen3 system. Explore the data model that powers your research.</p>

        <!-- STUDY -->
        <div class="doc-block" style="margin-top:28px">
          <h4>Study</h4>
          <p>The study table is shared between CDE and SGG studies. This table has a unique identifier for each study and some metadata and descriptions for each.</p>
          <p>For CDE the study table has the 4 studies and their descriptions:</p>
          <div class="card-grid" style="margin:16px 0">
            <div class="card"><div class="card__title" style="color:var(--color-accent)">NHS1</div><p>Nurses' Health Study 1</p></div>
            <div class="card"><div class="card__title" style="color:var(--color-accent)">NHS2</div><p>Nurses' Health Study 2</p></div>
            <div class="card"><div class="card__title" style="color:var(--color-accent)">NHS3</div><p>Nurses' Health Study 3</p></div>
            <div class="card"><div class="card__title" style="color:var(--color-accent)">GUTS</div><p>Growing Up Today Study</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="divider"></div>

        <!-- SUBJECT -->
        <div class="doc-block">
          <h4>Subject</h4>
          <p>The subject table is shared between CDE and SGG subjects. This table has a unique identifier for each subject (study participant) and metadata associated with them.</p>
          <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:16px">Fields of Interest for CDE Data</p>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">subject_id</p>
            <p>This is the participants 'Cohort ID' (their regular Nurses' ID including check-digit). For example: <code>'123456A'</code></p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">alias_id</p>
            <p>'External ID' or 'fake' ID used for external use of Nurses' data. These are 10 character IDs that start with 'X'.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">enrollment_date</p>
            <p>Participant enrollment date or study start date:</p>
            <ul style="margin:8px 0 0 20px">
              <li><strong>NHS1</strong> – 06/15/1976</li>
              <li><strong>NHS2</strong> – 06/15/1989</li>
              <li><strong>GUTS1</strong> – 06/15/1996</li>
              <li><strong>GUTS2</strong> – 06/15/2004</li>
              <li><strong>NHS3</strong> – 15th of the Month and Year that they responded to Mod1</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">active_status</p>
            <p>'active' or 'inactive' value depending on the participants current Name&amp;Address status value.</p>
            <p><strong>For NHS1, NHS2, and GUTS</strong> these are set to 'active' when they have any of the following status codes:</p>
            <ul style="margin:8px 0 0 20px">
              <li>0.address changed</li>
              <li>1.completed questionnaire</li>
              <li>5.telephone only</li>
              <li>6.short form only</li>
              <li>7.alive in this year (nhs1 &amp; guts) / 7.online short only (nhs2)</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:8px">Any other status is considered 'inactive' (2.refusal, 3.dead, etc.)</p>
            <p><strong>For NHS3</strong> any status code in the Name &amp; Address file is considered 'inactive' (M.max mod1 reminders, D.duplicate, etc.)</p>
            <div class="alert alert--info" style="margin-top:12px"><strong>Note:</strong> This indicates if the subject is actively participating in the study (or is eligible to receive more questionnaires). This does NOT indicate how recently they participated. We may not have heard from them for many years but they are still 'active'.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">opt_out_status</p>
            <p>Indicates that the person has an opt-out status of some kind in the opt-out file: 'all', 'dna', 'old', or 'sub'.</p>
            <p>Should be reflected in DER files (as either no record in DER file OR missing DOB in DER file). Non-missing opt_out_status indicates that for that type of data ('all', 'dna', 'sub') this person should be excluded from analysis.</p>
            <div class="alert alert--warning" style="margin-top:12px"><strong>Important:</strong> We want to save their data but observations from this subject should not be included in analysis.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">race</p>
            <p>Race categories following the federal standard (including 'multi-racial' and 'other' categories).</p>
            <ul style="margin:8px 0 0 20px">
              <li><strong>NHS1 and NHS2:</strong> From derived files – race9204 (NHS1; der7620) – race8905 (NHS2; der8919)</li>
              <li><strong>GUTS:</strong> Similar algorithm using combination of baseline and 2014 race reports, with participants mothers race used to fill missing responses</li>
              <li><strong>NHS3:</strong> Using mod1 responses, combined using same precedence as NHS1/2</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:8px">'Multi-racial' is assigned when more than one of the race fields is marked. 'Other/unknown' applies to 'Other' responses (NHS3 only) as well as no race response on a completed questionnaire.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">ethnicity</p>
            <p>Self reported 'Hispanic' or 'Not Hispanic' values from a combination of questionnaires for participant. This value comes from the same sources as the race field.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">sex</p>
            <p>This is meant to represent the participants natal sex or gender assigned at birth.</p>
            <ul style="margin:8px 0 0 20px">
              <li><strong>NHS1 &amp; NHS2:</strong> Simply set to Female (any participants later found to be male have been removed from the cohort)</li>
              <li><strong>GUTS:</strong> From the natal_sex field in gutsder9623</li>
              <li><strong>NHS3:</strong> From gender_m1 field in mod1 – "What sex were you assigned at birth, on your original birth certificate?" If missing, Name &amp; Address field 'gender' is used</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="divider"></div>

        <!-- INSTRUMENT -->
        <div class="doc-block">
          <h4>Instrument</h4>
          <p>An instrument can be thought of as a dataset belonging to a study. This table is CDE specific and contains a unique identifier and metadata for any CDE dataset that has been loaded into Gen3.</p>
          <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:16px">Fields of Interest</p>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">instrument_id</p>
            <p>This is a unique identifier for the dataset/instrument. This is mostly set to the SAS macro name.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
            <ul style="margin:4px 0 0 20px"><li><code>'nur12'</code></li><li><code>'der8917'</code></li></ul>
            <p style="margin-top:8px">Except for instances where the SAS macro has more than one cycle: <code>'n76'</code> vs <code>'n767880'</code></p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">instrument_name</p>
            <p>This is an alternate name for the dataset allowing duplicates. These should match the corresponding source SAS macro name.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
            <ul style="margin:4px 0 0 20px"><li><code>'NUR12'</code></li><li><code>'DER8917'</code></li><li><code>'N767880'</code></li></ul>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">instrument_description</p>
            <p>A description of the dataset/instrument.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
            <ul style="margin:4px 0 0 20px"><li>'NHS1 1998 Questionnaire'</li><li>'NHS1 1980 raw nutrient intakes'</li></ul>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">instrument_year</p>
            <p>This is the cycle year or mod associated with the instrument:</p>
            <ul style="margin:8px 0 0 20px">
              <li>For 'NUR' and nutrient data this is set to the 4 digit year of the associated cycle</li>
              <li>For CDX, DER and NHS3 MOD data this is set to N/A</li>
              <li>For NHS3 we don't really have a cycle year so it's blank in gen3</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">instrument_source</p>
            <p>A path and/or a more descriptive explanation of the data source. This won't be visible in the explorer.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="divider"></div>

        <!-- INSTRUMENT-FIELD -->
        <div class="doc-block">
          <h4>Instrument-Field (Variables)</h4>
          <p>The Instrument-Fields table is a collection of fields or variables associated with an instrument. Fields or variables in this table are unique but can occur in more than one instrument. This table is specific to CDE.</p>
          <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:16px">Fields of Interest</p>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">field_id (Variable ID)</p>
            <p>Unique identifier for each field or variable. This is typically set to the 'stem' name or the non-cycle portion of the variable name in the read macro.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Example:</strong> <code>'wt89'</code> would be set to <code>'wt'</code></p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px">These should be harmonized across cycles so that the same field/variable is associated with more than one dataset/instrument. For example, the same <code>'wt'</code> field_id will be associated with all 'wt' fields (wt89, wt91, wt93, etc.)</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">field_name</p>
            <p>I believe this redundant, I don't think we're using it. Same as field_id.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">field_description (Variable Description)</p>
            <p>A description of what the variable is observing. This is either a harmonized description of the field or simply the variable description from the data dictionary (as-is).</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Example:</strong> "smoking, cigarettes per day"</p>
            <p>In some cases this is the full Question as it appeared on the questionnaire.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="divider"></div>

        <!-- OBSERVATIONS -->
        <div class="doc-block">
          <h4>Observations</h4>
          <p>The observations table in our Gen3 data model is a simplified version of the observations table in the OMOP Common Data Model. This allows us to load any 2 dimensional dataset into Gen3. There is one record for every value-date-field combination (This allowed us to reduce the number of records from billions to millions).</p>
          <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:16px">Field Information</p>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">field_id</p>
            <p>This is the field of which the observation is from. This is the same unique identifier field_id from the instrument-field table.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">observation_date</p>
            <p>This is the date of the observation. All dates are set to the 15th of the month and year. This might be updated to 'months since enrollment' (integer values) in the future.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px">Depending on the source this can be defined in several ways:</p>
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:12px">Main questionnaires</p>
            <p>For observations from a questionnaire (nur15, mod1 etc.) this is the date of response for the questionnaire.</p>
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:12px">Derived files</p>
            <p>For derived file observations (der8919, der7620) this date is set to June 15th of the cycle year associated with the field_id observation.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
            <ul style="margin:4px 0 0 20px"><li>bmi89 – 06/15/1989</li><li>bmi91 – 06/15/1991</li></ul>
            <p style="margin-top:8px">If the source field isn't associated with a cycle ('BMI at 18' for example) the date defaults to the participants enrollment date.</p>
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:12px">Nutrient data</p>
            <p>For observations from a data file that is derived for a whole cycle (n84_nts, n84_ant) the date is set to June 15th of the cycle year for all observations in that file.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Example:</strong> All observation_dates from n20_atd are set to 06/15/2020</p>
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-weight:600;margin-top:12px">Disease followup data</p>
            <p>Observations from the disease files (nhs1_cdx_br_cases) are set to the diagnosis date (dxmonth) for the record.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">observation_text</p>
            <p>The observation value – numeric or character values.</p>
            <p>Formatted or categorical values are used when available rather than raw values.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Example:</strong> 1 vs 'yes' – observation_text will be 'yes'</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">source_instrument</p>
            <p>Instrument or dataset where the value for field_id was observed. This is a string value and corresponds to the instrument_id values.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="doc-block" style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent);margin:14px 0">
            <p style="color:var(--color-accent);font-family:monospace;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:6px">subjects</p>
            <p>List of subject_ids that responded to field_id with observation_text on observation_date. This will be displayed as a count of subject_ids in the explorer.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="alert alert--success" style="margin-top:16px"><strong>Key Insight:</strong> This structure allows for efficient querying and analysis of longitudinal data across multiple studies and timepoints, while maintaining data integrity and relationships.</div>
        </div>
      </section>
